AUTONOMOUS SUBSURFACE WATER EXTRACTION SYSTEM FOR MARS (ASWES-MARS)

Version 2.0 - Comprehensive Technical Specification Document
Classification: FOUNDATIONAL INDUSTRIAL INFRASTRUCTURE
Prepared for: MARTIAN SETTLEMENT & ISRU PROGRAMS CONSORTIUM

---

EXECUTIVE SUMMARY

The Autonomous Subsurface Water Extraction System for Mars (ASWES-Mars) represents the second pillar of Martian industrial infrastructure, complementing the metallurgical capabilities of AWR-Mars with life-sustaining water production. Designed as a continuous, autonomous, and scalable water production facility, this system transforms the Martian subsurface into a reliable water reservoir, enabling permanent settlement through closed-loop hydrologic systems.

Core Innovation Points:

· Thermal-Dominant Excavation: Melting/sublimation replaces mechanical drilling for reliability
· Phase-State Management: Active control of water through Mars' pressure-temperature instability zone
· Geophysical Intelligence: Real-time subsurface modeling directs extraction strategy
· Industrial-Plant Architecture: Designed for 95% operational availability over 5 Mars years
· Integrated Water Economy: Direct interfaces to electrolysis, agriculture, and industrial processes

Strategic Positioning: Where AWR-Mars builds the skeleton of civilization, ASWES-Mars provides its circulatory system.

---

1.0 MISSION PHILOSOPHY & DESIGN PRINCIPLES

1.1 Foundational Philosophy

Water is the non-negotiable prerequisite for permanent Martian presence. ASWES-Mars operationalizes the principle: "The first Martian industry must be water, because everything else depends on it." The system is designed not as a science instrument but as industrial infrastructure—the equivalent of terrestrial water utility systems adapted for autonomous operation on Mars.

1.2 Core Design Tenets

Tenet Engineering Manifestation
Thermal Over Mechanical 90% of subsurface access via phase-change, 10% via mechanical means
Stability Over Speed 10cm/hour penetration with guaranteed bore integrity vs. 1m/hour with collapse risk
Autonomy-By-Architecture 30-day continuous operation without Earth contact during dust storms
Water-as-Product, Not Sample Extraction rates measured in tons/sol, not milliliters/sol
Failure-Contained Design Single-point failures cannot cause catastrophic water release

1.3 Operational Context

· Primary Zones: Mid-latitude regions (30°-60° N/S) with known shallow subsurface ice
· Depth Range: 0-100 meters (optimized for 5-20m high-yield zones)
· Temperature Constraints: Operates -130°C to +50°C external, +1°C to +30°C internal water systems
· Atmospheric Interface: Manages phase transitions at 0.6 kPa ambient pressure
· Co-location: Deployed within 2km of primary habitat/industrial zones

---

2.0 SYSTEM OVERVIEW

2.1 Physical Specifications

Parameter Specification Notes
Class Stationary-Mobile Water Plant Moves between extraction sites, then anchors
Configuration Hexapod Walking Platform Maximum stability during drilling operations
Mass (Dry) 1,400 kg Without water load
Mass (Operational) 1,800-2,200 kg Includes extraction sleeves, water buffer
Height 3.2m (stowed) / 4.5m (deployed) Telescoping derrick system
Footprint 4m × 4m (anchored) Extendable stabilizers
Power System Mass 250 kg Integrated RTG + battery buffer
Thermal Plant Mass 320 kg Heat exchangers, phase control systems
Extraction System Mass 480 kg Derrick, thermal head, liner deployment
Anchoring Force 20 kN minimum Required for penetration reaction forces

2.2 Core Capabilities

Capability Specification Industrial Impact
Penetration Rate 0.1-0.3 m/hour in ice Conservative but reliable
Borehole Diameter 30 cm nominal Balance of volume vs. thermal efficiency
Maximum Depth 100 meters (design) Covers 95% of near-surface ice deposits
Water Production 100-500 kg/sol Scales with ice concentration (10-50% by mass)
Water Purity 99.5% after processing Directly usable for electrolysis
Energy Efficiency 0.5-1.0 kWh/kg water Depends on depth and ice concentration
Autonomy Duration 30 sols continuous Through communication blackout periods
Borehole Lifetime 90-180 sols Before thermal degradation requires relocation

