5.0 DEVELOPMENT ROADMAP

5.1 Technology Readiness Levels

Phase Duration TRL Goal Key Activities
1. Component 0-18 months TRL 4-5 Thermal head testing, liner deployment, phase control
2. Integrated 18-36 months TRL 6 Full-system vacuum chamber tests, Mars-analog trials
3. Field 36-48 months TRL 7 Devon Island/Atacama continuous operation
4. Qualification 48-60 months TRL 8 Flight unit build, environmental testing
5. Deployment 60-72 months TRL 9 Mars operations, production validation

5.2 Earth-Based Prototype (ASWES-E1)

Specifications:

· Scale: 1:1 functional prototype
· Environment: Thermal vacuum chamber with Mars simulant
· Testing Focus:
  1. 1,000-hour continuous operation
  2. 50 borehole cycles to 20m depth
  3. Phase transition management at 0.6 kPa
  4. Autonomous recovery from 20 fault scenarios

Analog Test Sites:

1. McMurdo Dry Valleys, Antarctica: Ice-cemented ground, cold
2. Devon Island, Canada: Permafrost, isolation
3. Atacama Desert, Chile: Hyper-arid, Mars-like soils
4. Iceland: Volcanic terrain with ice interfaces

5.3 Flight Qualification

Launch Environment:

· Vibration: 12.5 Grms overall
· Shock: 2,500 G peak (pyro)
· Acceleration: 5 G axial sustained

Mars EDL:

· Entry Mass: 1,800 kg (with aeroshell)
· Landing: Skycrane or retro-rocket platform
· Accuracy: <100m ellipse (for water field deployment)

Commissioning Sequence:

```
Sol 0-1: Landing, initial check
Sol 2-3: Mobility test, first anchoring
Sol 4-7: Instrument check, site survey
Sol 8-10: First penetration (5m target)
Sol 11-14: First water extraction (>10kg goal)
Sol 15-30: Ramp to 50% capacity
```

